# NanoClaw v2 — environment example.
#
# Copy this to `.env` (which is gitignored) and fill in real values for
# whichever channels you intend to enable. Each channel adapter's factory
# (in src/channels/<name>.ts) returns null when its required vars are
# missing, and the host logs `Channel credentials missing, skipping`
# instead of starting that adapter — so the daemon stays up on partial
# config; you only get the channels you've credentialed.

# ── LINE Messaging API ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# Source: LINE Developer Console → your provider → your channel
# (Messaging API).  Both vars are required for the adapter to register.
#
# When set, src/channels/line.ts opens its own HTTP listener on
# LINE_WEBHOOK_PORT (default 10280) at LINE_WEBHOOK_PATH (default
# /webhook), verifies inbound payloads against LINE_CHANNEL_SECRET via
# X-Line-Signature, and pushes outbound via api.line.me/v2/bot/message/push.
#
# Webhook URL to paste into the LINE Console (after the cloudflared
# tunnel is up — see _legacy/SECTION-3-LINE-TUNNEL-SETUP.md):
#   https://<your-tunnel-hostname>/webhook
#
LINE_CHANNEL_ACCESS_TOKEN=
LINE_CHANNEL_SECRET=
# Optional — defaults shown.  Only set these if you need to move the
# listener off 10280 (e.g. another process owns it) or rename the path
# (e.g. you want /line-callback for symmetry with another tool).  The
# cloudflared ingress rule and the LINE Console webhook URL must agree
# with whatever you set here.
# LINE_WEBHOOK_PORT=10280
# LINE_WEBHOOK_PATH=/webhook
